==English==
===Etymology===
Latin ''[[persuadere]]'', from ''[[suadere]]'', "to advise", "to recommend".
===Noun===
'''persuasion'''
#the act of [[persuade|persuading]] or the state of being [[persuade]]d
#the [[art]] of [[persuade|persuading]]
#:''It will require a master of '''persuasion''' to change his mind.''
#a [[strongly]] held [[conviction]], [[opinion]] or [[belief]]
#:''It is his '''persuasion''' that abortion should never be condoned.''
#(''informal'') (of a person) a [[sort]], [[type]], or [[kind]] with respect to [[conviction]]s and [[belief]]s
#:''You will find people of any '''persuasion''' among Wikipedians.''
#(Advertising) a research rating based on interviews pre- and post-viewing of an ad that measures how strongly a commercial’s messaging shifts consumer intention to purchase a product.
#:''The [[pre-test]]’s '''persuasion''' scores gave us a good indication of how effective our message was in the commercial with a straight pitch but was not useful for our “feel good” [[experiential advertising|experiential ad]].

===References===
for 5th definition, ''The Advertising Research Handbook'' Charles E. Young, Ideas in Flight, Seattle, WA, April 2005

